SIMPLE: sadden
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sadden
<hw>Sad"den</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Saddened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Saddening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make sad.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To render heavy or cohesive.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Marl is binding, and <qex>saddening</qex> of land is the great
prejudice it doth to clay lands.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To make dull- or sad-colored, as cloth.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>To make grave or serious; to make melancholy or
sorrowful.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her gloomy presence <qex>saddens</qex> all the scene.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sadden</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sadden
<hw>Sad"den</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become, or be made,
sad.</def> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sadder</ent>⟦br⟧
